    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-structure-input-format-handling/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We used the second version (September 2024) of the COCONUT database [15, 33] as our primary natural product structure source. Any compounds from the .sdf+ file that could not be read by RDKit were left out, leaving us with 695,129 compounds... We used Python [32] (v3.13.1) and the cheminformatic RDKit [21] package (v2024.09.4) as our main tools in Biosynfoni's creation and testing.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms RDKit is used to parse SDF files and convert to internal representation. However, the paper does not explicitly describe a task/skill for 'accepting multiple input formats and converting them' as a standalone operation. The paper uses RDKit to read SDF files from COCONUT, but does not document SMILES or InChI parsing as part of the Biosynfoni workflow in the passages provided. The research_question describes a general data-handling skill, but the paper's focus is on fingerprint design and evaluation, not on input format conversion as a primary research contribution.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-025-01081-6",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-structure-input-format-handling",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Accept molecular structures in multiple standardized input formats (SMILES, InChI, SDF files) and convert them to a common internal representation (RDKit Mol objects) for downstream fingerprint computation or analysis.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:24:22.212650+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-structure-input-format-handling/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "The paper does not describe biosynfoni as a command-line tool for parsing multiple input formats. Biosynfoni is presented as a molecular fingerprint (a data structure with 39 substructure keys), not as a parser or input-format converter. The paper states 'we used RDKit's Chem.Mol.GetSubstructMatches function for substructure key detection' but does not position biosynfoni itself as a CLI for format conversion.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-025-01081-6",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-structure-input-format-handling",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "biosynfoni (role: Command-line interface for parsing SMILES, InChI, and SDF inputs and converting them to internal molecular representation)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
