      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-structure-input-format-handling/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We used Python [32] (v3.13.1) and the cheminformatic RDKit [21] package (v2024.09.4) as our main tools in Biosynfoni's creation and testing... We used RDKit's Chem.Mol.GetSubstructMatches function for substructure key detection. Substructure keys are defined in SMILES ARbitrary Target Specification (SMARTS)... Any compounds from the .sdf+ file that could not be read by RDKit were left out",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms RDKit is used and that it parses SDF files. SMARTS (SMILES Arbitrary Target Specification) is mentioned, confirming SMILES-related functionality. However, the paper does not explicitly document InChI parsing by RDKit in the provided passages, though InChI is mentioned in the context of compound matching: 'Natural products were identified through InChI comparison to COCONUT compounds, where InChI parts 1\u20133 are identical'. The role described in the card (parsing multiple formats into Mol objects) is partially supported but not comprehensively documented in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-025-01081-6",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-structure-input-format-handling",
